# Recursive Maze-Solving System

I'll help you implement a recursive maze-solving system to find the shortest path through a 2D maze.

## Part A: Finding All Paths

```java
/**
 * Recursively finds all possible paths from start to end in the maze
 * @param maze The 2D maze
 * @param row Current row position
 * @param col Current column position
 * @param currentPath The path taken so far
 * @param allPaths Collection of all valid paths found
 */
public static void findAllPaths(int[][] maze, int row, int col, 
                               ArrayList<Point> currentPath,
                               ArrayList<ArrayList<Point>> allPaths) {

    // Check if out of bounds
    if (row < 0 || row >= maze.length || col < 0 || col >= maze[0].length) {
        return;
    }

    // Check if wall or already visited (value of 1 or 4)
    if (maze[row][col] == 1 || maze[row][col] == 4) {
        return;
    }

    // Check if we've reached the end
    if (maze[row][col] == 3) {
        // Add current position to path
        currentPath.add(new Point(row, col));
        // Create a new ArrayList to store in allPaths (to avoid reference issues)
        ArrayList<Point> completePath = new ArrayList<>(currentPath);
        allPaths.add(completePath);
        // Remove the end point for backtracking
        currentPath.remove(currentPath.size() - 1);
        return;
    }

    // Mark current cell as visited (4)
    int originalValue = maze[row][col];
    maze[row][col] = 4;

    // Add current position to path
    currentPath.add(new Point(row, col));

    // Explore all four directions
    findAllPaths(maze, row - 1, col, currentPath, allPaths);  // Up
    findAllPaths(maze, row + 1, col, currentPath, allPaths);  // Down
    findAllPaths(maze, row, col - 1, currentPath, allPaths);  // Left
    findAllPaths(maze, row, col + 1, currentPath, allPaths);  // Right

    // Backtrack: remove current position from path
    currentPath.remove(currentPath.size() - 1);

    // Restore the original value
